Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.00,0:00:05.00,Default,,0,0,0,,当我坐在一个人的对面,我很少能\NI've rarely sat down across  from somebody
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.00,0:00:09.38,Default,,0,0,0,,从他们口中表达出听出他们到底想要什么\Nand had them be able to articulate what do you acutally want
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.38,0:00:12.06,Default,,0,0,0,,他们没办法回答这个问题\NThey cannot answer that question
Dialogue: 0,0:00:12.06,0:00:17.46,Default,,0,0,0,,他们用瘾,爱好,想分泌更多的多巴胺来当答案.\N and they fill it with additions ,they fill it with hobbies,they fill it with dopamine chase.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.46,0:00:23.32,Default,,0,0,0,,他们用太多的东西当答案,却没人能真正的回答那个问题.他到底想要什么?\N They fill it with so much stuff and nobody can answer that question.What do you want?
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.32,0:00:28.64,Default,,0,0,0,,他们到是能回答出他们不想要什么.\N为什么他们自己会感觉到难受,是因为他们,他和她.\N It's what i dont want and why am i feeling  this uncomfortable.It's cos of them,It's cos of him,It's cos of her.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.64,0:00:36.70,Default,,0,0,0,,你想要的东西并不会自主出现,除非你开始追求它.\N你并不会追求它,除非你自己知道自己想要什么.\N Nothing  that you want will manifest itself unless you aim for it and you won't aim for it unless you know what it is.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.70,0:00:39.66,Default,,0,0,0,,你不知道你想要什么直到你问自己这个问题\NYou won't know what it is unless you ask yourself
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.66,0:00:46.54,Default,,0,0,0,,你会问自己为什么自己从来没有问过自己这个问题呢?\N也许答案是从来没有人给你解答这个问题到你需要的程度.\N光这个没有跟你解答问题到你需要的程度的事实,这就已经是一个很严肃的问题了\N and then you might say well why don't you ask yourself and the answer is well maybe no one ever explained to you that you needed to which is a crucial issue and
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.54,0:00:53.48,Default,,0,0,0,,也许自己本身就不信任自己.你会想如果我让我自己知道我到底想要什么\N and maybe you dont also trust yourself.Because you might think if i let myself know what i wanted.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.48,0:01:04.62,Default,,0,0,0,,从过往经验来看,我为了失败可谓是做了一切的功夫.\N所以我宁愿让我自己对本身不清不楚,这样我才不会让自己在重要的事上失败.\NGiven  my bloody track record,i would do everything i could to screw it up.So i'll just keep myself opqque to myself sothat i dont't fail at something that's truly important.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:04.62,0:01:12.92,Default,,0,0,0,,这样我就可以一直自我嘲弄的说,我没有成功是因为我没有努力过.\N如果我努力了,那么我早就成功了.\NI can alwa ys regale with myself with the diea that well i didn't succeed but i didn't really try hard.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.92,0:01:19.04,Default,,0,0,0,,但如果你让自己知道了你想要什么,然后你努力了.\N你也就为后续的失败满足了前置条件.\Nwhereas if you let yourself know what you want and then you try,you also set the precondition for failures.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:19.04,0:01:32.38,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:32.38,0:01:41.44,Default,,0,0,0,,youtube上的,或者其它平台上的朋友,大家好.今天来的是Dr John deloney.\Nhello everyone.watching and listening on YouTube or one  of the associated podcasts.I'm here today with Dr John deloney.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.44,0:01:48.86,Default,,0,0,0,,他是own your past,change your future的作者.\N我们讲讨论这本书.我也很开心能和另一个医师进行交流.\Nhe's the author of own your past change your future.We are gonna talk today.Im  very happy to do this,talk to another clinician.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.08,0:01:58.14,Default,,0,0,0,,关于你的人生就是一个经历,你通过经历中来观察世界,\N以及当事情走向偏差时,你经历就会随着发生的变化\Nabout the fact that you live your life through a story that you see the world through a story what that stody might be like when things are going wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.14,0:02:05.94,Default,,0,0,0,,我们也会提及你的身份和身份的变化和发展\N How it might be approved and also to talk about identity and its tranformations in the most practical possible way.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.94,0:02:16.14,Default,,0,0,0,,我们有大多可以谈论的事情了.我们可以从你为什么对经历感兴趣开始,John\Nand so um there are specifics that we can talk about but that's a good place to start what got you so interested in stories
Dialogue: 0,0:02:16.14,0:02:30.14,Default,,0,0,0,,我先了解到了精神创伤的后果会在人身上潜伏10-30年,\N因为这个,我开始对过去经历感兴趣.\N um I I think it I reverse engineered my way into it um it was learning the trauma narrative that played out in the human body 10 15 30 years later after the initial trauma
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.14,0:02:44.26,Default,,0,0,0,,我以前一直认为人生故事就是经历,过去就过去了.\N 我一直没理解到,来引用van der kolk的话,我的身体在一直在我不知不觉的情况下,\N在与过去经历做斗争.\Nand so I've always thought stories were narrative right there was something I thought about I did not understand that my body was keeping the score to quote van der kolk right that my body was revving up in fighting battles that  I didn't even know was happening
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.26,0:02:58.48,Default,,0,0,0,,然后我们通过长期数据看到了,人们因为儿童时的经历中风,\N癌症心脏病发作.这让我认识经历在各个方面上都有影响.\N and so we're looking at the long-term data man and people are having strokes and cancer and heart attacks from from childhood experiences and that made me step back and go whoa there's there's these different layers to these stories happening all over the place and
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.48,0:03:08.70,Default,,0,0,0,,当我思考后,我发现经历不只是过去的事情.它是我们整个人的一部分,是人生经验的一部分.\Nit's not just narrative it's it's the entire ecosystem that I call my body right my Human Experience and then as I began to pull the thread on those man
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.70,0:03:20.28,Default,,0,0,0,,这些经历是我们不可分割的一部分.他们决定了我们生活的经验,\N他们构成了我们对自己是谁的认知.\Num those stories were born into and the stories we were told have such a formative shaping of of of our life experience and those stories become the stories we tell ourselves
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.28,0:03:36.32,Default,,0,0,0,,我们作为精神医生从业者知道经历定义了一切.让我们知道自己能干什么,\N不能干什么,让我们知道知道自身的存在就是对自己最大的恶.\N这些经历可以限制我们的发挥,也可以是我们美好生活的助推剂\N which as we all know in mental health professionals that shapes everything who I think I am and what I think I'm capable or not capable of or I'm the worst thing to ever happen to me those stories are highly limiting or they are the jet fuel on and on a well-lived life right
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.32,0:03:42.36,Default,,0,0,0,,如果我们能讨论这些经历,这会给我们带来极大的帮助\Nso if we can discuss those stories man what a shape-shifting opportunity for us
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.36,0:03:54.12,Default,,0,0,0,,身体存储过去经历的想法很有趣,我对它的理解是,\N yeah well that idea about stories in some sense being stored in the body is kind of interesting and so the way I conceptualize it is that
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.12,0:04:03.12,Default,,0,0,0,,过去的经历在你的个性中显现,在你的目标中显现,在你的对世界的假设和认知中显现.\N a story manifests itself in a in  personality in a set of goals and a set of assumptions about the world perceptions about the world and
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.12,0:04:12.98,Default,,0,0,0,,如果你过去有不好的经历,其实所有人都有不好的经历,只是或多或少而已\N if you have had terrible things happen to you in the past and that's pretty much true of ever of everyone although some people more than others
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.98,0:04:23.38,Default,,0,0,0,,你的身体根据你过去的糟糕经历,到现在还念念不忘的糟糕经历,来计算当前环境下的危险程度\N then your body computes the present danger of the environment based on how many things have happened to you that are terrible in the past that that aren't resolved and.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.38,0:04:43.04,Default,,0,0,0,,解决了的糟糕经历意味着你已经为它们开发了一个解决方案.\N如果的心理生理系统还认为你曾经经历的的那些遭遇还依然存在在现在的环境中,\N那么它会让你精神紧张就如同你即将要再次经历那些遭遇一样\N resolved would mean that you had generated a solution for them and if you if your psychophysiological system assumes that all the danger that you were subject to Once is still present in the environment that it's going to set you on edge as if you're walking in dangerous territory
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.04,0:05:01.40,Default,,0,0,0,,这样的心理生理上的后果就是,你在不知不觉中为了抵御潜在的危险,\N将感知系统变得更敏锐,但这却比正常状态消耗更多能量.\N and the psychophysiological consequence of that is that you're prepared for danger and that does such things as burn up excess resources because you're much more reactive and on point than you might otherwise be in an anxiety prone manner
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.40,0:05:11.90,Default,,0,0,0,,这也使你的免疫系统得到抑制.因为你现在就在面临危险,你的身体已经顾不上长远的健康问题了\N it also suppresses immunological function.because your body isn't that worried about long-term immunological Health if you're confronting an emergency.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:11.90,0:05:42.18,Default,,0,0,0,,你在你的书里谈论掌控你的过去.这对找到战胜过去挫折的手段有帮助.\N这些手段可以让那些挫折不在是你心理生理上的负担,也可以让你再次遇到这些挫折的概率无限接近于零.\N so that you you talk in your book about changing your past owning your past and it's useful to Define that you're likely to overcome a trauma let's say and no longer in some sense store it psychophysiologically if you've generated a causal story about the reason that the trauma emerged and then reconfigured the way that you're conducting your life so that the probability that a similar thing will happen to you is reduced to close to zero
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.18,0:05:46.08,Default,,0,0,0,,这些不是发泄情绪,而是理解问题.\N right it's not catharsis right it's understanding yeah
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.08,0:06:14.76,Default,,0,0,0,,我觉得问题的根源就在我们现在社会在心理层面的特质.我们创造了一个指责的社会,\N每件事有需要有人负责.我们只能对自己的生存范围进行无限切分\N(为了让自己承担的责任更少?),直到我们脚下的方寸之间.\N而你踏入到了我的区域就是对我或意识形态或物理上的侵犯.\Nthe challenge there is I think we've following that thread all the way to our modern psychological ethos we've created a world that is based entirely on blame and like somebody else is responsible and so I've got to continue to cut and cut and cut and I reduce myself to a two by two square with which I can exist and if you enter my Square then whether it's ideologically or physically then suddenly you're affronting me and.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.76,0:06:44.96,Default,,0,0,0,,我认为掌控你的过去意味着,当你回首过去,\N当然我们都知道记忆是个很主观的东西,我不在意当时到底发生了什么.我现在40岁了,\N我现在更关注的是,当我选择重新沉浸在当时挫折之中时,\N我的身体不会不经思考的下意识做决定,企图快刀斩乱麻.\N而是它知道我在思考,在等待我大脑做出的决定.\N I think there's something about owning your past I look at it more in terms of can I think through what I remember to happen have happened and by the way we know that memory is a disastrous like narrative Storyteller right so I care less about what actually happened and more I'm in my 40s I'm telling myself this story that happened can I tell that story can I relive that story and my body doesn't take off on me right it doesn't rush to solve the problem for me\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.96,0:07:11.64,Default,,0,0,0,,记忆关键的一点就是它根本没办法提供一个客观准确的记录,\N单纯因为这是根本不可能的,因为过去是个太过复杂的事务了.它更像是一个地图,\N我在这里发生了一些可怕的事情.提醒我需要重新更新我的地图,从而让我不会落入同样的陷阱.\n the thing about memory is that it's not there to provide an accurate objective record of the past which is in fact impossible because the past is so unbelievably complex it's more like a navigation tool which is I went here I fell into something terrible and now I need to re-calibrate the navigation map that I'm using so that I don't fall into the same hole.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.64,0:07:33.04,Default,,0,0,0,,我觉得在听的观众你们需要知道的一点就是,\N如果一个已经发生了18月的记忆还在不断,不自主的在你的记忆里纠缠着你.\N当它出现的时候,你的身体不自觉得产生压力,\N因为它还觉得你仍然在危险之中.\N and you know one of the things that people might want to know who are listening is that if you have a memory that's older than about 18 months and it haunts you and when it comes up involuntarily it produces a stress reaction what that means is that as far as your nervous system is concerned and so as far as your body's concerned that danger hasn't gone away.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.04,0:07:47.58,Default,,0,0,0,,这是因为有一个潜意识的警报系统在不断的探测可能的危险,\N它在提醒你,你现在用的地图是一个不完善的,继续使用会使你再次掉落进之前的坑中.\N and what's happening is an unconscious alarm system that's looking for pitfalls and holes is warning you that the map that you're using is incomplete in a manner that might might enable you to fall into the same hole.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.58,0:08:14.34,Default,,0,0,0,,一个针对这个很好的策略就是,与其等待过去的挫折不由自主的浮现,\N不如主动的刨悉你比以前的那个你发生了什么样的变化,什么改变了,什么没改变,\N以及想一个策略来,如果同样的情况袭来,\N你该如何比之前站在一个更有利的位置上\N,and so one of the things that people can do that's very useful is if you have memories like that that plague you is to bring them to mind voluntarily instead of waiting for them to come after you involuntarily and then to Think Through what has changed and what might not have but also to come up with a plan so that if a similar circumstance arose you'd be in a better position in one way or another to deal with it.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.34,0:08:55.00,Default,,0,0,0,,世上没有其它办法能让一段记忆消散,\N如果只是一遍遍的用相同的思维反复回想.\N这段记忆会一直纠缠你.它会出现在你的幻想里,\N出现在你的梦境中,出现在你与他人的对话里,只因聊天的话题涉及了它.\N话题可能是关于一次失败,而你过去的经历就是一次失败.\N如果你手中的地图并不能有效的让你超越过去的挫折的话,你大脑中确定危险的那部分是不会让你忘记挫折的.\N there's no other way of getting the memory to go away like merely re-contemplating it in the same manner over and over won't do it and allowing it to plague you unconsciously it'll do that forever until you solve it it might show up in your dreams it'll show up in your fantasies it'll trigger you so to speak when you're talking to other people if they happen to discuss a topic that's related to it and it's because that the narrative is one of failure and defeat the event was one of failure and defeat and if there isn't a map to allow you to transcend that that's functional then the part of your brain that is concerned with identifying danger is never going to let you go.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.00,0:09:24.36,Default,,0,0,0,,我认为,我们在文化上创造出了这种病态的不安(逃避?),\N你刚才表述的很清楚,唯一救赎的办法就是微笑的面对他,尝试开始解决问题.\N如果继续选择逃避,只是在怪罪你当初的行为的话.你就是过度分析一切.\N而直面恐惧则允许你的身体通过和别人的关系以及生活中的其他事逐渐的康复\Nyeah and I I think culturally we've created a pathology of discomfort and as you just outlined so eloquently the only way through this is to turn and face it and walk directly through it right and if you continue to run from the memories and pathologize and Chase the behaviors you end up with our over diagnostic approach to everything instead of turning and facing these things and letting your body heal through relationships and other things in your life
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.36,0:09:51.16,Default,,0,0,0,,hhh 我们只是在重复你之前说过的话,你说了好几次了.你逃避的越多,\N你的身体就越以为你的挫折在战胜你,因为你在朝着远离挫折的方向逃避.\N这会不断加强你的挫败感.你逃的越远,你心理层面上的疾病越强.但唯一治愈的手段就是面对.\N我们给我们自己创造的文化确告诉我们要尽一切可能远离一切的不安.但面对问题是唯一的解决途径.\Num man we just end up chasing your tail and you   the more you run the more your body thinks it 's winning it's getting away from this stuff so it actually reinforces the anxiety it reinforces some of these um like psychological ailments the further you run from it the only healing is through it and in the culture we've created for ourselves says that uncomfortable discomfort is bad and it's to be avoided at all costs it and it's it's the only path to Healing
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.16,0:10:54.48,Default,,0,0,0,,广告
Dialogue: 0,0:10:54.48,0:11:21.38,Default,,0,0,0,,如果逃避,你的大脑就会接收到你逃避的东西已经超出你的能力范围了,所以你就很自然的选择躲避.\N 而躲避是会导致焦虑的.当然直面恐惧不是一件容易的事情.\N所以你在你的书里提到了一系列的方法可以帮助直面恐惧.\N比如可以帮助你区别恐惧的方法,恐惧也有大有小,当然柿子挑软的捏.\Nif you run then the signal that the story you're acting out is that the  thing you're running from is bigger than you and that you have to hide and that's just a recipe for anxiety now it's not necessarily that easy to turn and face something but you do detail out a variety of strategies in your books that might help people do that you can you can differentiate the problem like you might you might have been traumatized at work let's say
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.38,0:11:50.36,Default,,0,0,0,,我们就不用专业词汇了.如果你在办公场所遇到了极大的麻烦.\N你的上司是一个暴君,你觉得工作真的很没有意义,这些想法一直在纠缠你,\N以至于到了打扰你休息的地步.你尝试摒弃这些念头,但无一成功.部分原因是重新找一个工作实在是太吓人了,你没办法承受.\N or let's not use that sort of jargony that jargony phraseology you may be having tremendous difficulties at work you might bedealing with people who are tyrannical at work and find it very meaningless and so and that's bothering you constantly it's disturbing your sleep for example and It's haunting you and you're you tend to try to push it out of your mind when the thoughts come and partly that's because the thought of how getting a new job is so daunting that you can't face it and.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:50.36,0:12:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,一个解决方案可以是把一个大问题分成几个小但仍可以解决的自问题.\N还是以工作举例的话,就是你感到不开心想找到一个新的工作,第一步可以是打开你的简历.\N虽然你可能找不到一个新工作,但是你至少打开了你的简历.\N one of the ways of re-calibrating that is to break down the problem into small and manageable steps and so for example one of the things that you can do if you might have to consider getting a new job because you're unhappy and miserable at work is open up your resume or your CV and look at it right so you might not be able to get a new job but you might be able to open up your resume and look at it and
Dialogue: 0,0:12:17.00,0:12:38.42,Default,,0,0,0,,这样做你开启了伟大征程的第一步.\N你可以在接下来的一个月,每周花一个小时改你的简历,也可以每天花10分钟改一下,\N也可以每两天花10分钟改一下.技巧的关键就是把一个骇人的,让你恐惧到逃避的怪兽,变成一个你能处理的程度.\N and then having done that you've sort of cracked the surface and then maybe you could spend an hour a week for a month updating it or 10 minutes a day or 10 minutes every two days something like that but part of the trick is to take these larger monsters that are frightening enough so you want to run away from them
Dialogue: 0,0:12:38.42,0:13:02.34,Default,,0,0,0,,你在你的书里提到了你问了很多人为什么觉得有些事情事会他们感到焦虑不安.然后让他们写原因,\N然后问他们自己为什么认为这些是正当的理由,然后开发一个计划来处理各个理由\N you lay out for example in your book you ask people a lot of different questions about what they're thinking and if something is making you anxious and Afraid and miserable it's very useful to lay out to write out all the reasons it's making you anxious and miserable and to ask yourself what is it you're afraid of and then to develop a differentiated plan for dealing with those.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.34,0:13:28.48,Default,,0,0,0,,让我问你一个问题,在你精神分析的职业生涯中,\N到底有没有人,到底大多数的人能不能靠自己做的我们说到的这些.\N 因为我发现不管从现代人的心理的每个问题出发,\N我都得到了同样的答案,就是现代人绝望地,病态地,心灵层面地,吓人地孤独了\nso let me ask you this in your psychoanalytic experience can somebody can the majority of people do this by themselves because I if I was to distill down all of the pathologies in modern civilization I keep coming back to a central one Central Point and that's that we are desperately and pathologically and spiritually and frighteningly lonely.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:28.48,0:13:38.67,Default,,0,0,0,,我在想我们是否还能告诉一个21岁的男孩/男人,你得自己独自做这件事\Nyeah and I'm wondering if we we can is it even possible anymore to tell a 21 year old boy 21 year old man hey you need to do this by yourself.
